Rust's concurrency model vs Go's concurrency model: stackless vs stackfull coroutines

June 20, 2024

This post is part of my Summer Autumn of Rust 2024 series: weekly (or more) quickies about how to write great Rust code so you will be ready to rock at the end of the summer and find a new exciting job ðŸ¤˜ Dont forget to Subscribe (Email & RSS)

While Rust and Go are both modern programming languages that have learned from the mistakes of the previous generation, they manage concurrency in a completely different way, which, as we will see, has a huge impact on performance and developer experience.

But first, why do we need concurrency?

Today, most programs interact with resources that can take time to return a response: the network or a disk for example. It would be a pretty inefficient use of our hardware if we would completely block the execution of our programs while waiting for a response from the network!

This is why Go and Rust have built into the languages features that let programs execute other tasks when one is stuck waiting for I/O (Input/Output).

But, what is a task?

Tasks

Tasks are abstract units of computing that can be executed concurrently: multiple functions can be processed (by the program) at the same time, but they are not necessarily executed (by the CPU) at the same time (it's parallelism which requires multiple threads).

You can spawn new tasks in Go with the go keyword:

go doSomething()
go doAnotherThing()

While in Rust you need to use the spawn function:

tokio::spawn(async move {
     do_something().await
});
tokio::spawn(async move {
     do_another_thing().await
});

In both cases, the tasks are processed at the same time by the language's runtime.

But, what is a runtime?

The Runtime

The purpose of a runtime is to manage and schedule the different tasks for an efficient use of the hardware.

This is where Rust and Go first differ. You can't change your Go runtime (unless you use a completely different compiler such as tinygo), it's kind of built into the language, while in Rust no runtime is provided by the language, you have to bring your own.

Note: In this post we are going to discuss async Rust with the tokio runtime, which is the most used and versatile runtime unless you are programming tiny microcontrollers.

Functions give back control to the runtime when they are waiting for something (the network for example). This is done automatically in Go by the standard library, the language and the compiler, while in Rust it happens when an await keyword is reached.

Stackfull coroutines

Stackfull coroutines are also called green threads, goroutines or M:N threading (M green threads running on N kernel threads) is the concurrency model adopted by Go.

In this model, the runtime manages lightweight (green) threads and schedule them on the available hardware threads. Like kernel threads, each task have their own stack, which can be grown by the runtime if required.

The first problem with stackfull coroutine is that each task has its own stack which means that each task uses a minimum amount of memory. As of Go 1.22, the minimum amount of memory used by a goroutine is 2 KiB which means that if you have 10,000 concurrent task running, your program will use at least 20 MiB of memory.

The second problem with Stackfull coroutine is that the runtime needs complete control over the stack layout which make interoperability with other languages (such as C's FFI) difficult as the runtime has to do some work preparing the stack before being able to call C code. That's why CGO is considered slow (in reality CGO calls are done in 30 to 75 nanoseconds, which is pretty fast in my opinion).

Seeking a breakthrough in your career? It's time to learn Rust! Take a look at my book Black Hat Rust to learn how to write secure and production-ready Rust code.

Stackless coroutine

On the other hand, Rust has adopted the stackless coroutine approach where tasks don't have their own stack. In Rust, Futures are basically simple structures implementing the Future trait where each .await chain is compiled into giant state machines.

The problem with async

If you are developing in Python or C# you may already know the big cost of async/await: function coloring where sync function can't call async function and vice versa.

This leads to many problems such as a fragmentation of the ecosystem where libraries aren't interoperable: it's difficult to use libA in your program because your are using async but not this lib, but also to many mistakes from developers who block the event loops of the runtimes and bring down the performance of the system.

This is exacerbated in Rust first because the standard library doesn't provide the same async functions as the sync ones (e.g. read which reads an entire file) and because the different runtimes aren't even interoperable together: if you start writing your program for the tokio runtime, you will have a hard time porting it to another runtime.

All of this is solved in Go where, everything is sync and the compiler and the runtime automagically insert await points when calling async functions that are invisible to the programmers, but as we saw, it comes at the cost of a performance penalty (memory and CPU).

Some Closing Thoughts

While Rust approach allows to get the most out of the machine, it comes with a fragmented ecosystem which is causing great troubles to Rust adoption: the foundations are not stable, the efforts are not focused and every organization have to reinvent the wheel many times.

To learn more about concurrent programming and how runtimes work under the hood take a look at my articles Async Rust: Cooperative vs Preemptive scheduling and Async Rust: What is a runtime? Here is how tokio works under the hood.

Finally, I recommend the article Why async Rust? to learn more about the motivations of the team that brought async Rust to life.
